Motivated by Refs. [15, 31], suppose that the total population N(t) can be divided into four compartments, that is, S(t), E(t), I(t), and R(t), where S(t), E(t), I(t), R(t) denote the susceptible, exposed, infectious, recovered individuals at time t, respectively. Consider the SEIR-type epidemic model with time delay and vaccination control which is presented as following functional differential equation:1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} \left\{ \begin{array}{l} {\dot{S}}=\mu N_0(1-u(t))-\frac{\alpha S(t)I(t-\tau )}{N_0}-\mu S+\delta R, \\ {\dot{E}}=\frac{\alpha S(t)I(t-\tau )}{N_0}-\left( \beta +\mu \right) E, \\ {\dot{I}}=\beta E-\left( \gamma +\mu ^{I}\right) I, \\ {\dot{R}}=\mu N_0u(t)+\gamma I-\left( \delta +\mu \right) R, \end{array}\right. \end{aligned}$$\end{document}S˙=μN0(1-u(t))-αS(t)I(t-τ)N0-μS+δR,E˙=αS(t)I(t-τ)N0-β+μE,I˙=βE-γ+μII,R˙=μN0u(t)+γI-δ+μR,where all parameters are nonnegative (see Table 1 for details), u(t) is a vaccination control needed to design. u(t) can be seen as a vaccination rate [13, 28]. The flow diagram for model (1) is presented in Fig. 1. This epidemic model involves the following assumptions: 
There exists a vector between susceptible and exposed individuals. The vector will become infectious after a time \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\tau >0$$\end{document}τ>0. The susceptible population in S enter into E when they come into contact with infected vectors.
The population in E move to I after the average latent time \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\beta ^{-1}$$\end{document}β-1.
Part of the recovered people become susceptible again to the disease.
The death rate in I is large than the natural death rate.Fig. 1
The flow diagram for model (1)

Note that the vector may be an animal (mosquito) [12] or a human (asymptomatic infection) [5]. Based on Assumption 1), in model (1), the total number of infections per unit of time at time t is given by \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\frac{\alpha S(t)I(t-\tau )}{N_0}$$\end{document}αS(t)I(t-τ)N0, which is called “true-mass action model” [31]. The model (1) can be used to describe the case that there exist many asymptomatic infections, such as COVID-19. In Sect. 5, we will use our model to simulate the second outbreak of COVID-19 in Italy and show the effectiveness of the proposed vaccination control.

